com.github.basking2.sdsai.dsds

Class BTree<K,STOREKEY,V>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.github.basking2.sdsai.dsds.BTree<K,STOREKEY,V>
  • Type Parameters:
    K - The user key type. See Map for its use.
    STOREKEY - The storage key that K will be transformed in to. The NodeStore must be able to convert a K to a STOREKEY and must be able to generate a STOREKEY for storing internal nodes.
    V - The user value type. Sett Map for its use.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    BTreeMap<K,V>, java.util.Map<K,V>

    public class BTree<K,STOREKEY,V>
extends java.lang.Object
implements BTreeMap<K,V>

    A B-Tree that uses a NodeStore object to persist Nodes and user data to blob storage. This is tailored to NoSQL document / key-value systems.

    There is no concurrency built into this object so edits to a BTree must be coordinated through a locking mechanism or some otherwise atomic service. Developers looking to add transactionality should consider implementing a NodeStore to collect and atomically batch-update edits.

      • BTree

        public BTree(K rootKey,
             NodeStore<K,STOREKEY,V> nodeStore,
             int minData)

        Attempt to retrieve the root node stored at the rootKey or, if none is found, construct a new empty root node with minData*2 as the size of the maxData value to the Node's constructors.

        The rootKey will never be altered where as internal nodes are not guaranteed to have the same key.

        Parameters:
        rootKey - The key at which the BTree's root is stored.
        nodeStore - The storage engine.
        minData - The minimum amount of data that this BTree will store in a Node. The maximum data will be minData*2+1 and the number of child Nodes will be one more than that.

      • clear

        public void clear()
        Clears the datastructure by doing a depth-first node traversal to delete all the user data and the node data from the NodeStore. This uses eachDepthFirst(com.github.basking2.sdsai.dsds.node.NodeFunction<K, STOREKEY>) to visit each node. Notice that this will not delete the root Node key as other pieces of code may be accessing this object.
        Specified by:
        clear in interface java.util.Map<K,V>

      • destroy

        public void destroy()
        Whereas clearing will destroy all but the root node, this method calls clear() and deletes the root node key.

      • eachDepthFirst

        public void eachDepthFirst(NodeFunction<K,STOREKEY> callable)
        Recrusively depth-first execute NodeFunction.call(Node) on each. This is used by clear() to destroy the datastructure in an orderly way. This is the same order provided by getNodeIterator() and NodeLocation.
